//! {{Name}} host-image driver: a [`crate::FrameSource`] scaffold generated by `fpdev new-driver`.
//!
//! ## Status
//!
//! **Scaffold — hardware-unverified.** Every device value here (VID/PID, endpoints, frame geometry,
//! the init/deinit byte sequences) is a placeholder marked `HW-verified: required`. The driver
//! compiles and self-verifies against scripted bytes (see `mock_tests`), so the *shape* is proven
//! from minute one; capturing from a real sensor needs those placeholders confirmed against the
//! hardware. The living proof that a driver of this shape captures and matches is the `vfs5011`
//! worked example under `usb/`, which shares this exact layering.
//!
//! ## Provenance (read before editing)
//!
//! This tree is **original code**, generated from the parameterized `fpdev new-driver` templates and
//! modeled on the `{{from}}` worked example — it is **not** transliterated from any libfprint driver.
//! Copying an LGPL driver's expression would make this a derivative work and break the permissive
//! core (see `ARCHITECTURE.md` §Provenance & licensing, `docs/adding-a-driver.md`). Interoperability
//! *facts* — a USB VID/PID, an endpoint number, image geometry — are not copyrightable and may be
//! matched freely; state them here as facts, and write the framing as your own Rust.
//!
//! ## Layering (mirrors `usb/`)
//!
//! - [`proto`] is pure `Vec<u8>` framing / encode / parse — no transport, no `nusb`, unit-tested on
//!   any platform.
//! - [`{{name}}`] holds the device constants and the init/deinit sequences, expressed in the
//!   [`crate::usb::wire`] vocabulary.
//! - `source` is the [`crate::FrameSource`] generic over any [`crate::usb::UsbTransport`], so
//!   `ImageDevice<{{Name}}FrameSource<NusbTransport>>` runs the host-image pipeline over real
//!   hardware and `ImageDevice<{{Name}}FrameSource<ScriptedTransport>>` runs the same path over
//!   scripted bytes.

